# Mashup Manager — Cursor AI Rules
# Author: Tushaar Mungul <tushaar.mungul@spoonconsulting.com> — Spoon Consulting

# H5 SDK Mashup — Cursor Rules
# Place this file at the ROOT of your Angular H5 SDK project

## 1. PROJECT STRUCTURE
- All M3 API calls must be defined in a SHARED SERVICE (e.g. api.service.ts)
- Never write API calls directly inside a component
- Components call the shared service methods only
- Keep business logic in services, keep components clean for UI only

---

## 2. USER CONTEXT INITIALIZATION
- UserContext must be initialized BEFORE the app starts loading
- Do NOT initialize UserContext in ngOnInit
- Use APP_INITIALIZER in app.module.ts to load UserContext at bootstrap
- Refer to SampleH5SDK projects to understand the correct UserContext initialization pattern
- Example pattern:
  providers: [
    {
      provide: APP_INITIALIZER,
      useFactory: (userContextService) => () => userContextService.init(),
      deps: [UserContextService],
      multi: true
    }
  ]

---

## 3. app.component.html STRUCTURE
Every app.component.html MUST start with exactly these 2 lines first:

<soho-icons-new></soho-icons-new>
<soho-icons-empty-new></soho-icons-empty-new>

Then immediately after, add the masthead section:

<section class="masthead">
  <div class="flex-toolbar" data-options="{maxVisibleButtons: 6}">
    <div class="toolbar-section">
      <button type="button" class="masthead-icon">
        <svg class="icon icon-logo" focusable="false" aria-hidden="true" role="presentation">
          <use href="#icon-logo"></use>
        </svg>
        <span class="audible">Go To Home</span>
      </button>
    </div>
    <div class="toolbar-section title">
      <h1 class="masthead-appname">{{appTitle}}</h1>
    </div>
    <div class="toolbar-section buttonset">
      <button type="button" class="btn" id="versionbtn"
        (click)="headerPanelVersion()">{{appVersion.version}}</button>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

Refer to SampleH5SDK\C04-Cuisson-Pomme\src\app\app.component.html for the full reference structure.

---

## 4. API CALL PATTERN
All M3 API calls MUST follow this exact structure inside the shared API service:

async call_[ProgramName]_[TransactionName](param1: string, param2: string): Promise<any> {
  try {
    const inputRecord = new MIRecord();
    inputRecord.setString('FIELD1', param1?.trim());
    inputRecord.setString('FIELD2', param2?.trim());

    const request: IMIRequest = {
      program: 'PROGRAMNAME',
      transaction: 'TRANSACTIONNAME',
      record: inputRecord,
      maxReturnedRecords: 0,
      outputFields: []
    };

    const response: IMIResponse = await this.miService.execute(request).toPromise();

    if (response.hasError()) {
      return [{ error: true, errorMessage: response.errorMessage }];
    }

    return response.items.length > 0 ? response.items : response.items;
  } catch (error: any) {
    console.error("Error:", error);
    return [{ error: true, errorMessage: error.message || error }];
  }
}

Rules for API calls:
- Method naming: call_[ProgramName]_[TransactionName]
- Always use ?.trim() on all string inputs
- Always check response.hasError() before returning
- Always wrap in try/catch
- maxReturnedRecords: 0 means no limit — use by default
- outputFields: [] means return all fields — use by default unless specific fields needed
- For standard M3 APIs: always verify program, transaction, inputs and mandatory fields
  against CursorInstructions\API_List\API.json
- For custom APIs (CMS100MI, MDBREADMI, EXT...MI): full input/output description MUST
  be provided in requirement.md — never guess custom API fields

---

## 5. ASSETS FILES — REQUIRED IN EVERY PROJECT

Two files MUST always exist under src/assets/:

### 5.1 src/assets/api.json
- Stores ALL M3 API calls used in this project
- Must be kept in ASCENDING ORDER by program name, then transaction name
- Every time a new API call is added to the shared service, update this file
- Refer to SampleH5SDK\C04-Cuisson-Pomme\src\assets\api.json for the exact format
- Example structure:
  [
    {
      "program": "CMS100MI",
      "transaction": "LstC04_CUISSOND",
      "description": "List cuisson data",
      "inputs": ["F_RDAT", "T_RDAT", "F_WMST", "T_WMST", "VMFACI"],
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "program": "MMS200MI",
      "transaction": "GetItmWhsBas",
      "description": "Get item warehouse basic data",
      "inputs": ["WHLO", "ITNO"],
      "outputs": ["WHLO", "ITNO", "STQT", "ALQT"]
    }
  ]
- Always maintain alphabetical/ascending order: programs A→Z, then transactions A→Z within
  the same program
- Never leave this file empty or outdated — it must reflect exactly what is used in the project

### 5.2 src/assets/parametre.json
- Stores the version of the project and any global parameters
- Refer to SampleH5SDK\C04-Cuisson-Pomme\src\assets\parametre.json for the exact format
- Must be updated every time a new version is released
- Example structure:
  {
    "version": "1.0.0",
    "appName": "MAH33 Cuisson Pommes",
    "environment": "production"
  }
- The version value is what gets displayed in the masthead via {{appVersion.version}}
- app.component.ts must load this file at startup and expose it as appVersion

---

## 6. TRAINING RESOURCES — ALWAYS CONSULT BEFORE IMPLEMENTING

### 6.1 M3 API List
- Location: CursorInstructions\API_List\API.json
- Use this to verify: program name, transaction name, input fields, output fields, mandatory fields
- Never assume or guess an API field — always check api.json first
- Custom APIs are NOT in api.json — get their definition from requirement.md

### 6.2 Sample H5 SDK Projects
- Location: SampleH5SDK\ folder in the project root
- Always refer to these for: project structure, module setup, UserContext init,
  service patterns, component patterns
- These are validated projects — inherit their patterns faithfully
- Key reference: SampleH5SDK\C04-Cuisson-Pomme\src\app\app.component.html
- Key reference: SampleH5SDK\C04-Cuisson-Pomme\src\assets\ for api.json and parametre.json format

### 6.3 Infor Standard Components Library
- Location: Mashup Manager\Components Library\scraped_components\
- Always use scraped component code as the base for any Soho IDS component
- To find the right component:
  1. Go to the component subfolder (e.g. scraped_components\button\)
  2. Pick the correct .html variant for your use case
     (e.g. example-disabled-button-tooltip_html)
  3. Extract ONLY the code below the <span>IDS Enterprise</span> tag
  4. That is the implementation-ready component code

---

## 7. GENERAL CODING RULES
- Always use TypeScript strict typing
- Never use 'any' unless absolutely necessary and justified
- Always use async/await — never raw .subscribe() for API calls
- Always handle errors gracefully — never let API errors crash the UI
- Always use Soho IDS components:
  soho-grid, soho-button, soho-input, soho-dropdown,
  soho-datepicker, soho-lookup, soho-accordion, etc.
- Never use plain HTML <input>, <button>, <select> —
  always use their Soho IDS equivalents
- Follow Angular best practices: OnPush change detection where possible,
  unsubscribe on destroy

---

## 8. REQUIREMENT FILE
- Before implementing any feature, always check requirement.md at the project root
- requirement.md contains:
  - Feature description and business logic
  - Custom API definitions with full input/output fields
  - Any specific rules or constraints for this project
- If requirement.md does not exist, ask the user to provide it before proceeding
  - **Translation**: `TranslocoDirective` + `@jsverse/transloco`
